there was no way

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:02.890
digital photography was ever
going to take over film.

00:03:02.890 --> 00:03:05.890
And this poor guy that was there
in this booth was one

00:03:05.890 --> 00:03:08.490
step out the door, because
nobody's going to buy an

00:03:08.490 --> 00:03:10.570
electronic camera!

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:13.120
And the big photographers that
were willing to do it wanted

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:15.480
hundreds of thousands of
dollars, because any pictures

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:18.380
that they took would be useless
to them forever.

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:22.210
And me, right out of
college, went, I'll

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.970
do it for the camera.

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:30.330
And that's really right
place, right time.

00:03:30.330 --> 00:03:34.750
And be willing to be paid in
orange shortbread cookies.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:39.910
That's really what
it comes down to.

00:03:39.910 --> 00:03:42.580
So what I want to talk about how
it all interplays, because

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:43.580
it all interplays.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:46.450
Everything dovetails into
everything else.

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:51.940
I'm going to start with passion
in the photograph.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:56.720
The quickest way to take better
photographs is to stop

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:59.960
taking photographs.

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:04.060
Let the photograph take you.

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:06.610
Be taken by your pictures.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:13.590
It is not about smile
now, damn it!

00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:17.880
It is about that moment
where you go [GASPS].

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:23.370
And as you're being grabbed, the
journey is not this way.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.360
The journey is this way.

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:27.510
And as you're being ripped
through that lens, watching

00:04:27.510 --> 00:04:33.670
cool things happen, the finger
should be shooting.

00:04:33.670 --> 00:04:37.610
I shoot so much that according
to my doctor, I have a stress

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:41.660
fracture on this finger
and these fingers.

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:44.200
I couldn't figure out why my
hand was killing me, and it's

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:46.630
like, well, how much did
you shoot when you

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:47.630
were in Burma last?

00:04:47.630 --> 00:04:48.330
And I'm looking at it.

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:52.340
I have 136,000 frames.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:54.570
His response was, perhaps
shoot less.

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:58.520
My response was, rebuild me.

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:03.640
So the response, it has to
be absolutely automatic.

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:06.200
Things travel at the
speed of life.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:09.110
And rather than noodling the
photograph and concerning

00:05:09.110 --> 00:05:14.260
yourself about did I get
it right, forget that.

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:17.200
What you need to get
is you need to let

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:18.590
the moment take you.

00:05:18.590 --> 00:05:22.480
You need to let the moment that
moved you to the point

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:26.260
where you are witnessing the
most amazing thing be the

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:28.700
impulse to fire.

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:32.040
Things happen at the speed of
life, and a camera captures

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:34.330
things in fractions
of a second.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:36.850
We see things in time
and motion.

00:05:36.850 --> 00:05:40.660
A camera photographs things
in fractions of a second.

00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:47.270
When adding up how much time I
have spent in Burma or India

00:05:47.270 --> 00:05:47.720
or wherever--

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:50.380
I just did this with Burma--
when I was done, I was there

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:54.050
for two weeks, and if you total
up all the fractions of

00:05:54.050 --> 00:06:00.240
seconds that I shot, I shot
two and a half minutes.

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.020
But I was there for two weeks.

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:05.580
I have stress fracture
on my shooting hand.

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:06.150
Why?

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:07.100
It's a numbers game.

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:08.490
Things happen at the
speed of life.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:12.440
You set your camera up so that
it can do all of the things

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:15.020
that you don't want to worry
about, exposure,

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:16.730
focus, those things.

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:18.250
If you think about a D4--

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:20.720
I shoot Nikon, so I'm going to
speak in a Nikon metaphor--

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:25.300
if you think about a D4, D800,
those cameras, those are the

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:28.770
ultimate idiot-proof, or as we
like to refer to the computer

00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:34.390
business, an ID10T camera,
total point and shoot.

00:06:34.390 --> 00:06:34.790
Why?

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:37.820
Because I am busy concerning
myself about what is happening

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:39.450
in front of my camera.

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:43.370
I do not want to worry about
what my camera is doing.

00:06:43.370 --> 00:06:45.850
To your question, how do you
make technology better?

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:49.420
You make it so that I can set it
up, and it does the things

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:54.100
I need it to do based on my
style, that there is some form

00:06:54.100 --> 00:06:56.300
of understanding of what it
is that I'm shooting.

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:58.750
One of the advantages of my
system is the way in which its

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:01.060
meter works, which is
why I choose it.

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:04.640
It's a three-dimensional light
meter that's an RGB meter with

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:07.190
6.5 million pixel RGB meter
that meters in three

00:07:07.190 --> 00:07:09.750
dimensions, and computes skin
tones, and backgrounds, and

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:12.240
things differently, so it
exposes differently.

00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:13.280
Why?

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:17.470
I don't want to be paying
attention to all of that.

00:07:17.470 --> 00:07:19.750
I need to be paying
attention to what?

00:07:19.750 --> 00:07:22.210
The moment as it unfolds
in front of me.

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:28.620
The architect Mies van der Rohe
said, "An interesting

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:34.720
plainness is the most difficult
thing to achieve."

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:38.940
You want to have "blow
you away" pictures?

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:41.340
Photograph interesting
plainnesses, things that

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:45.890
others walk by so that you
create an image that stops the

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:49.850
viewer the same way
you were stopped.

00:07:49.850 --> 00:07:54.020
The conversation in a
photograph is this.

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:56.830
Ansel Adams was asked, how
many people are in your

00:07:56.830 --> 00:07:57.420
photographs?

00:07:57.420 --> 00:08:02.370
And he said, well, me.

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:03.930
No.

00:08:03.930 --> 00:08:07.060
The only thing I disagree with
him on all of his quotes is

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:09.150
the one person that doesn't
belong in your

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.160
photograph is you.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:15.070
And here's the reason why,
in my philosophy of it.

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:17.610
Things happen in the
space between.

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:19.400
Photograph doesn't happen
over here, and it

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:20.430
doesn't happen over here.

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:24.160
It happens in this space,
the space between.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:27.460
In karate, the reason why you
throw a punch and pull out

00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:32.380
fast, versus planting it, is
that if you plant it, 90% of

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:34.030
the force of the impact
is left in the

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:35.150
hand if it's there.

00:08:35.150 --> 00:08:40.320
If it comes in and pulls out,
90% of the impact is here.

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:43.890
Where do you want the impact
of your photograph to be?

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:45.330
In the photograph.

00:08:45.330 --> 00:08:48.410
You want to create an image so
that it's as if the person who

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:52.300
is looking at it was standing
in the same place that you

00:08:52.300 --> 00:08:56.610
were when the photograph
took you.

00:08:56.610 --> 00:08:59.650
So if you can get to that
point, that's a

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:01.230
great place to be.

00:09:01.230 --> 00:09:06.150
Well, how do you get to
that point, would be

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:06.940
a question to ask.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:09.880
Do we agree on that?

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:13.570
Mr. Stuff, I'm about
to tell you.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:16.230
How you get to that point is you
understand the middle part

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:18.410
of photography forwards,
backwards, upside down,

00:09:18.410 --> 00:09:22.020
sideways, in any other
dimension, since we can talk

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:24.020
string theory here, and
you'll understand

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:27.190
what I'm talking about.

00:09:27.190 --> 00:09:32.300
And then at point of capture,
promptly forget it.

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:35.540
There's a concept in Japanese
thought, in Zen Japanese

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:38.990
thought, called shibumi, which
is the ability to have

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:41.660
thoughtful, thoughtless thought,
to do the right thing

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:45.480
at the right time, in the
moment, without consciously

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:47.020
thinking about doing it.

00:09:47.020 --> 00:09:48.060
You simply be it.

00:09:48.060 --> 00:09:49.900
You simply do it.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:53.290
How you get there is
through practice.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:57.490
There's a misnomer that practice
makes perfect.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:09:58.890
Practice does not
make perfect.

00:09:58.890 --> 00:10:00.200
Perfect practice
makes perfect.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:02.050
You have to practice
at practicing.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:06.360
One of the great sorrows I have
as a teacher is I will go

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:09.560
to exotic places with people,
and I will do what I always

00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:11.550
do, which is what would
you like this

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:13.350
conversation to be about?

00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:16.420
And somebody will say to me,
well, I came here to learn how

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:19.440
to use my camera better.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:22.810
How much money, time, and
effort did you spend for

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:25.260
buttonology lessons?

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:28.220
When you walk into the hairball
of photography, you

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:30.000
need to know that camera as
well as you know yourself.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.490
Sun Tzu, "The Art Of War."
It's a great book on war.

00:10:33.490 --> 00:10:34.520
It's a great book on life.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:35.620
It's a great book on art.

00:10:35.620 --> 00:10:38.000
You know your camera as well as
you know yourself, you will

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.880
know the outcome of
every photograph.

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:42.720
Know your camera half as well as
you know yourself, you get

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:44.980
half the shots, you lose
half the shots.

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:47.900
Don't know your camera means
you don't know yourself.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:49.630
You were truly lost.

00:10:49.630 --> 00:10:50.880
So where do you practice?

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:53.700
You practice here, where
it doesn't matter.

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:55.860
You carry a camera with
you everywhere you go.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:59.420
You drive your cat crazy, your
significant other crazy, your

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:02.350
kids crazy, your
friends crazy.

00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:02.770
Why?

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:03.900
Because you're crazy.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:06.400
You decided to do photography,
right?

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:10.020
I mean, there are many more
things that one could do that

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:15.666
would be less nuts-making
than photography.

00:11:15.666 --> 00:11:17.480
I'll give you another
question to ask you.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:21.340
When you look at somebody's
work, do you know if

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:23.270
it's good or bad?

00:11:23.270 --> 00:11:25.080
When you look at a picture,
you can say,

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:26.470
that's good, it's bad.

00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:28.740
I like it, I don't like it.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:29.910
You can do that.

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:32.180
You can go through these
pictures up here, and you will

00:11:32.180 --> 00:11:34.990
make judgments as to whether or
not they're good or bad to

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:38.400
your aesthetic, correct?

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:42.220
Why can't you do that
with your own work?

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:45.040
Why can't you look at your own
pictures and say, this is

00:11:45.040 --> 00:11:46.230
good, this is bad?

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:49.160
Why is it all crap?

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:52.340
Furthermore, why did you
choose a hobby in which

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:56.290
everything you do, you say
to yourself is what?

00:11:56.290 --> 00:11:57.390
It's crap.

00:11:57.390 --> 00:11:58.130
Really?

00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:00.450
There are enough people to
beat you up in the world.

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:02.860
You do not need to assist.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:05.840
Your biggest critic sits in
the same chair you do.

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:08.580
I contend that, no,
it isn't crap.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:13.120
What the problems are is
understanding stuff.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:14.450
Technology.

00:12:14.450 --> 00:12:18.820
It is this interesting thing
that we do with technology.

00:12:18.820 --> 00:12:21.350
We blame ourselves for the
problems of the technology,

00:12:21.350 --> 00:12:23.100
and we blame the technology for

00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:25.980
problems that are ourselves.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:30.730
For example, a camera
meters at 18% gray.

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:33.500
That means if I shoot a white
wall and a black wall, and I

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:35.580
let the meter do it, I'm
going to get what?

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:38.170
Two 18% gray walls.

00:12:38.170 --> 00:12:41.300
So we go out in this highly
dynamic, highly lit

00:12:41.300 --> 00:12:42.680
environment, we take
a picture, and

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:43.730
it comes out flat.

00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:46.210
And we say to ourselves,
I suck.

00:12:46.210 --> 00:12:46.490
No!

00:12:46.490 --> 00:12:48.140
The camera meters at 18% gray.

00:12:48.140 --> 00:12:51.440
What sucks is the camera
meters at 18% gray.

