00:17:40.590 --> 00:17:46.140
It has come down to why this
matters with something called

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:49.090
depth of field.

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:51.410
My favorite definition of depth
of field is Michael

00:17:51.410 --> 00:17:55.900
Reitman's, which is a circle
of confusion is a bunch of

00:17:55.900 --> 00:17:59.400
photographers sitting around a
table defining depth of field.

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:08.850
So let's talk about depth of
field and the illusion of

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:10.060
depth of field.

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:11.740
Let's agree on terms.

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:13.640
What are the parameters
of depth of field?

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:16.740
Aperture, do we agree?

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:18.620
Focal length.

00:18:18.620 --> 00:18:20.820
Distance from a subject.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:23.540
And if you want more crap in
focus, you stop the lens down.

00:18:26.100 --> 00:18:27.450
No.

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:29.830
Focal length has nothing
to do with it.

00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:33.320
Distance of the subject does,
aperture does, and something

00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:36.350
called angle of view.

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:40.520
All lenses have the same
depth of field.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:43.480
Why a wide-angle lens appears
to have a greater depth of

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:47.850
field than a telephoto lens
has to do with this.

00:18:47.850 --> 00:18:50.770
The smaller an object is,
the more in focus

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:52.080
it appears to be.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.670
The bigger an object is,
the less in focus

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:55.940
it appears to be.

00:18:55.940 --> 00:18:59.110
How many people shot film?

00:18:59.110 --> 00:18:59.530
OK.

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:02.260
For those of you who don't shoot
film, I agree, film is

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:04.740
what occurs in your teeth now
when you don't brush.

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.830
But back in the day, 35
millimeter film, if you looked

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:09.985
at a contact sheet, all
the pictures would

00:19:09.985 --> 00:19:10.820
be in focus, right?

00:19:10.820 --> 00:19:13.250
It wasn't until you put it in
the enlarger that all hell

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:14.640
broke loose.

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:15.330
Why?

00:19:15.330 --> 00:19:18.840
Because as you blew the image
up, that's when you started to

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:20.270
see the blur.

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:24.050
The tighter the edge,
the more in focus.

00:19:24.050 --> 00:19:26.030
The less coherent, the
bigger it is, the

00:19:26.030 --> 00:19:28.420
less in focus it becomes.

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:29.730
That's the first thing.

00:19:29.730 --> 00:19:31.170
Here's another proof.

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:34.820
An 80 millimeter lens on the
35 millimeter camera is a

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:37.500
telephoto lens, correct?

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:38.750
Slight telephoto,
but telephoto.

00:19:38.750 --> 00:19:43.320
If we call 50 normal, 80 would
be in the realm of telephoto.

00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:46.950
An 80 millimeter lens on 2.25
camera is the normal lens, and

00:19:46.950 --> 00:19:49.680
an 80 millimeter lens on a
4 by 5 view camera is a

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:50.660
wide-angle lens.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:53.180
What changed?

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:55.830
Angle of view.

00:19:55.830 --> 00:19:58.100
So that's the first thing
to keep in mind.

00:19:58.100 --> 00:20:02.570
I will get to why that
matters in a second.

00:20:02.570 --> 00:20:07.630
The next one is the misnomer of
if you stop the lens down,

00:20:07.630 --> 00:20:11.080
you get more things in focus.

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:17.250
That is not true according
to physics.

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:20.905
Unless you can introduce, my
favorite word in photography,

00:20:20.905 --> 00:20:25.135
the Scheimpflug principle--

00:20:25.135 --> 00:20:26.890
cool word, isn't it?

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:28.790
Swings and tilts.

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:31.490
Unless you can do this, if
you're dealing with a

00:20:31.490 --> 00:20:35.520
fixed-lens system, which is
what this is, physics says

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:39.920
that the only thing that is in
focus is that which the lens

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:44.290
is physically focused upon and
anything that crosses the

00:20:44.290 --> 00:20:47.200
plane of focus.

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:49.940
That means that anything from
the plane of focus is the

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:53.880
increasing area of acceptable
out of focus,

00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:56.630
though it isn't in focus.

00:20:56.630 --> 00:21:00.590
Now why we believe this to be
true has to do with film.

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:04.250
A lens, any one of these lenses
here, is capable of

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:09.760
resolving a minimum
of 200 line pair.

00:21:09.760 --> 00:21:14.050
That's 200 black and white
lines per centimeter.

00:21:14.050 --> 00:21:19.600
Film was between 150 and 170
line pair, which means that

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:22.310
the lens has greater resolution
than the film.

00:21:22.310 --> 00:21:24.820
With me so far?

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:29.470
Silver paper was between
50 and 75 line pair.

00:21:29.470 --> 00:21:31.550
So the lens has greater
resolution than the film, and

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:33.600
the film has significantly
greater resolution than the

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:35.500
photographic paper,
silver paper.

00:21:35.500 --> 00:21:39.830
So anything above 75 line pair
will register as what?

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:41.290
75 line pair.

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:43.720
So you have the illusion of more
things in focus, but in

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:47.620
reality, what you have are more
things at 75 line pair.

00:21:47.620 --> 00:21:52.180
Digital, the lens sees 200,
the sensor sees 200, and

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:55.000
high-end printers can print
upwards of 300 line pair,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.450
which means that the output
device has greater resolution

00:21:57.450 --> 00:21:58.720
than the file that you're
sending it.

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:01.220
So what are you going to see?

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:03.830
Blur ramp.

00:22:03.830 --> 00:22:07.080
So this brings up a very
interesting question, which

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:13.260
goes back to yours, yours,
yours, and trust me when I

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:16.520
tell you, yours.

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:18.580
Trust me.

00:22:18.580 --> 00:22:21.820
Which is, what's your photograph
more about, in

00:22:21.820 --> 00:22:23.202
focus or in blur?

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:30.782
What do you worry about more,
in focus or in blur?

00:22:30.782 --> 00:22:32.930
You worry about in
focus, right?

00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:35.220
But only one thing in your
photograph's in focus.

00:22:35.220 --> 00:22:38.550
So you're spinning your wheels
worrying about less than 1% of

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:40.730
the image when most
of your image is

00:22:40.730 --> 00:22:44.020
about the ramp of blur.

00:22:44.020 --> 00:22:44.580
Here's another one.

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:46.790
You want four objects in
a photograph in focus?

00:22:46.790 --> 00:22:49.910
What do you know you need?

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:52.120
Four photographs.

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:56.840
Because you can't have four
objects in focus in a digital

00:22:56.840 --> 00:23:00.540
camera because of
the resolutions.

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:03.930
The trick with the photograph
is that when you're all said

00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:07.480
and done, it looks like you
didn't do anything, and the

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:10.670
person looking at your
photograph will believe that

00:23:10.670 --> 00:23:12.240
they could go right
out and shoot it.

00:23:12.240 --> 00:23:14.560
And at the same time, what
you've done is that when they

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:17.800
look at a flower, if you took
a picture of a flower, for

00:23:17.800 --> 00:23:20.050
that much time they
see your flower.

00:23:20.050 --> 00:23:23.350
Then they see the flower that
they're looking at.

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:27.130
How you accomplish this task
and where pretty is in a

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:27.690
photograph--

00:23:27.690 --> 00:23:31.620
and if you want to pick one of
the great epiphany moments of

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:35.570
my career visually, to answer
how do you do this, was when I

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:38.780
realized that my photograph was
more about the blur than

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:41.050
it was about the focus.

00:23:41.050 --> 00:23:43.590
All lenses focus.

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:45.860
That is what lenses do.

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:46.740
That's their job.

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:50.250
But it is how they handle from
in focus to blur, which is

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:53.060
where the pretty is.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:56.060
Are you making the seed packet
photograph, or you're trying

00:23:56.060 --> 00:23:57.950
to make a piece of art?

00:23:57.950 --> 00:24:00.270
Are you putting something in the
Encyclopedia Britannica,

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:03.310
or the Encyclopedia Americana,
or Wikipedia, or you're trying

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:05.980
to make something that
moves somebody?

00:24:05.980 --> 00:24:07.060
That's the question.

00:24:07.060 --> 00:24:09.680
If what you're trying to do is
accurately document something,

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:12.420
then focus, stack the thing, put
it [? in Helicon ?] focus,

00:24:12.420 --> 00:24:15.180
make one big in focus
photograph, and call it a day.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:18.920
If what you're trying to do is
to move the viewer's eye

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:22.970
around the photograph and tell
the story you want to told,

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:25.650
because you want to move the
viewer in a certain way, then

00:24:25.650 --> 00:24:28.410
we're in a different realm.

00:24:28.410 --> 00:24:30.920
And the more you understand
the physics

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:32.570
of this, the math--

00:24:32.570 --> 00:24:36.170
and what is a great thing for
me is that I give this

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:39.560
discussion quite a bit, and
the fact that everybody in

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:42.330
this room could probably correct
me on my math really

00:24:42.330 --> 00:24:44.150
makes my day.

00:24:44.150 --> 00:24:47.390
So you have to understand
how these work.

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:51.490
For example, does light travel
in a straight line?

00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:54.470
Not according to Einstein.

00:24:54.470 --> 00:24:56.830
According to Einstein,
light bends.

00:24:56.830 --> 00:25:00.110
Light's both a wave and a
particle at the same time.

00:25:00.110 --> 00:25:02.090
The reason why these lenses are
designed the way they are

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:03.410
is so that red, green,
and blue hit the

00:25:03.410 --> 00:25:05.090
sensor at the same time.

00:25:05.090 --> 00:25:07.810
Nothing about the journey of
light down this barrel is a

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:08.520
straight line.

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:10.960
It does move in a forward
direction, but it doesn't move

00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:13.500
in a straight line.

00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:17.980
So natural light has a whole
different set of things that

00:25:17.980 --> 00:25:23.140
it does, attributes, that
strobe light doesn't.

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:25.940
It's both ambient and
directional at the same time.

00:25:25.940 --> 00:25:27.070
You can light in a ball.

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:30.390
Hot light works the same way,
which is why I tend to use

00:25:30.390 --> 00:25:32.370
those lights, that
type of lighting,

00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:34.320
because it's prettier.

00:25:34.320 --> 00:25:38.360
It's also the more difficult
and the simpler types of

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:39.680
lighting to do at
the same time.

00:25:39.680 --> 00:25:41.840
It requires a greater
understanding of how light

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:45.035
works to be able to shoot
it, but it's everywhere.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:51.210
What I look at when I look at
these is the bokeh of the

00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:54.170
