00:27:01.540 --> 00:27:05.240
color space, way I want it to
white balance, how I want

00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:08.060
picture control to handle
things, at what speed I'm

00:27:08.060 --> 00:27:09.180
going to shoot.

00:27:09.180 --> 00:27:12.710
I put this on aperture priority,
and I have a

00:27:12.710 --> 00:27:16.370
focusing system that
[SNAPS], OK?

00:27:16.370 --> 00:27:18.610
So it's not the little green
button which decides

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:19.430
everything for me.

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:23.620
I decide before I walk in what
it is that I think the

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:26.060
environment is going
to require from me.

00:27:26.060 --> 00:27:29.260
I also shoot in the raw,
but not in the buff.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:31.930
I'll be very clear about that.

00:27:31.930 --> 00:27:34.190
That will get you arrested.

00:27:34.190 --> 00:27:38.040
The reason why I shoot in the
raw is a raw file allows me to

00:27:38.040 --> 00:27:39.700
rebake a cake.

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:44.810
The only thing that I can't
unto is ISO and bad

00:27:44.810 --> 00:27:46.590
photography.

00:27:46.590 --> 00:27:49.680
Other than that, I can
change everything.

00:27:49.680 --> 00:27:53.070
So I come up with a set of
parameters that I think will

00:27:53.070 --> 00:27:58.250
fit, and I want to offload as
much as I possibly can the

00:27:58.250 --> 00:28:02.270
things that I don't want to
worry about, like exposure.

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:05.090
I want this camera calling the
ball whenever possible on

00:28:05.090 --> 00:28:06.680
exposure, because it will
do it better than I

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:09.150
can, most of the time.

00:28:09.150 --> 00:28:12.040
I want this camera
auto-focusing

00:28:12.040 --> 00:28:13.910
because it will focus--

00:28:13.910 --> 00:28:14.830
because of these, right?

00:28:14.830 --> 00:28:18.150
Sharper than I can, and
quicker than I can.

00:28:18.150 --> 00:28:19.930
Because what I want to be
doing is I want to be

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:22.550
practicing on reacting
to the moment.

00:28:22.550 --> 00:28:25.960
So that's why I picked this
camera system, because the

00:28:25.960 --> 00:28:29.230
camera system allows me to set
it up, and it's kind of my

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:30.960
little green button.

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:33.440
So did I connect that for you?

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:34.420
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:28:34.420 --> 00:28:35.140
VINCENT VERSACE: OK.

00:28:35.140 --> 00:28:36.190
So that I practice.

00:28:36.190 --> 00:28:38.210
And then the other thing that
is important is I can tell

00:28:38.210 --> 00:28:42.750
what's going on with my camera
by the sound of the shutter.

00:28:42.750 --> 00:28:43.810
That's important.

00:28:43.810 --> 00:28:45.710
Like if I'm in a really dark
room, and I'm hearing click,

00:28:45.710 --> 00:28:49.560
click, click, that's
ISO, way too high.

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:51.580
Or if you're outside on a bright
day, and you're just

00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:55.430
hearing that camera shoot off
at an 1/8,000 of the second,

00:28:55.430 --> 00:29:00.240
that tells you you haven't
done something correctly.

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:04.840
So it's understanding the
majority of what the menus do

00:29:04.840 --> 00:29:07.250
on the back and how to set
it up is important.

00:29:07.250 --> 00:29:10.330
Again, it's understanding the
system so completely that when

00:29:10.330 --> 00:29:13.000
you set it up, you don't have
to worry about it, that you

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.400
can hear by sound what is going
on, that by the way in

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:20.570
which the camera is shooting
tells you that something is or

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:24.130
is not correct on it.

00:29:24.130 --> 00:29:26.640
I always do something called
VSE, Visual Search of

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:27.320
Extremities.

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:29.270
When the camera is in the camera
bag, and I pull it out,

00:29:29.270 --> 00:29:31.020
the first thing I do is turn
it on just make sure

00:29:31.020 --> 00:29:32.770
everything is set right.

00:29:32.770 --> 00:29:35.790
Because there are gremlins that
live in camera bags, and

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:37.600
they turn the camera on, they
push the buttons, and they

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:38.430
turn it off.

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:40.380
And all of a sudden,
you don't know.

00:29:40.380 --> 00:29:42.390
Or somebody decides they want
to look at your camera.

00:29:42.390 --> 00:29:44.430
They play with all
your buttons.

00:29:44.430 --> 00:29:48.240
I was out shooting in Burma,
and somebody played with my

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:49.510
camera, and put it into JPEG--

00:29:52.850 --> 00:29:56.720
I don't know what's
below garbage.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:58.710
And I'm shooting this picture,
and it's like bing, bing,

00:29:58.710 --> 00:29:59.636
bing, bing, bam!

00:29:59.636 --> 00:30:02.420
And it's like, something's
not right.

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:03.900
And I shot this entire
sequence of

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:08.630
JPEG basic in SRGB.

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:10.990
And it was just, like, really?

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:13.214
A little closer, just
a little closer.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:17.690
This gets into the other
part of it, which

00:30:17.690 --> 00:30:20.270
is camera as canvas.

00:30:20.270 --> 00:30:23.560
I have two D800s,
a D600 and a D4.

00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:29.150
One D800 is converted for
infrared, and then I have the

00:30:29.150 --> 00:30:33.030
D600, and the D4,
and the D800.

00:30:33.030 --> 00:30:38.410
Why would I possibly want to
have that many different types

00:30:38.410 --> 00:30:41.590
of resolution in a camera?

00:30:41.590 --> 00:30:46.390
I don't want to shoot a portrait
at 36 megapixels.

00:30:46.390 --> 00:30:49.250
That's like retouching
an orange.

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:51.430
That's hours of work.

00:30:51.430 --> 00:30:52.890
I want a, nice, smooth
skin tone.

00:30:52.890 --> 00:30:54.570
I want to be able to shoot
at very low light

00:30:54.570 --> 00:30:55.330
when I shoot a portrait.

00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:55.530
Why?

00:30:55.530 --> 00:30:58.310
Because lower light has
a prettier quality.

00:30:58.310 --> 00:31:00.310
I want to shoot a landscape, so
what am I going to shoot?

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:02.850
I'm whipping out that D800,
thank you very much.

00:31:02.850 --> 00:31:06.500
I have no idea what is going to
face me when I go to shoot.

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:07.820
What camera do I pick?

00:31:07.820 --> 00:31:08.520
D600.

00:31:08.520 --> 00:31:09.190
Why?

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:15.910
4,000 ISO, no noise, 24
megapixels, no problem.

00:31:15.910 --> 00:31:18.320
Each camera is a different
canvas that

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:19.280
does a different thing.

00:31:19.280 --> 00:31:20.630
It's a different tool.

00:31:20.630 --> 00:31:23.620
And each one of these lenses
combined with that creates a

00:31:23.620 --> 00:31:24.880
different look.

00:31:24.880 --> 00:31:28.010
So what I'm going to do is I'm
going to show you a bunch of

00:31:28.010 --> 00:31:33.850
images in which what I would
like you to see here, first,

00:31:33.850 --> 00:31:36.720
is my commitment to the moment,
which is the things

00:31:36.720 --> 00:31:39.630
that move me, and you're going
to see some of the infrared

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:40.560
stuff as well.

00:31:40.560 --> 00:31:42.130
And we will get into that.

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:45.690
And you're going to see a
journey of my life, part of

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:47.310
which is all the different
places I go.

00:31:47.310 --> 00:31:49.640
Because, you see, my photographs
really are the

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:53.590
snapshots of the vacation
that is my life.

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:56.895
I'm amazed that I get
paid to do this.

00:31:56.895 --> 00:32:00.490
I'm happy I get paid to do this,
but there's a different

00:32:00.490 --> 00:32:05.435
story than the photograph tells,
that the photograph--

00:32:05.435 --> 00:32:06.600
how do I put this?

00:32:06.600 --> 00:32:09.400
The photograph tells one story,
but there's a different

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:11.620
story behind each photograph.

00:32:11.620 --> 00:32:13.690
I'm going to tell you one story
about one photograph

00:32:13.690 --> 00:32:15.100
after I show you this.

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:16.989
So let's see if this works.

00:32:16.989 --> 00:40:41.977
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:40:41.977 --> 00:40:45.630
VINCENT VERSACE: Proof that
children are indeed born in

00:40:45.630 --> 00:40:48.720
cabbage patches.

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:52.810
So what you should see is that
there's a lot of use of blur

00:40:52.810 --> 00:40:55.570
in that photograph and a
lot of use of focus.

00:40:55.570 --> 00:41:00.580
And the objects that I want
you to see are in focus.

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:06.100
There's some other things that
I do, which is I don't really

00:41:06.100 --> 00:41:10.310
pay too much attention to
composition theory,

00:41:10.310 --> 00:41:14.230
particularly 17th century
painting composition theory.

00:41:14.230 --> 00:41:17.570
Rule of thirds, Grecian mean,
the center of the frame is for

00:41:17.570 --> 00:41:20.370
God, not you, or the center of
the frame is the best place to

00:41:20.370 --> 00:41:21.640
put the object.

00:41:21.640 --> 00:41:23.420
You decide.

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:26.660
What I pay attention to is the
biomechanics of vision.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:29.610
What is looking at
the picture?

00:41:29.610 --> 00:41:35.990
17th century composition theory
or a set of eyeballs?

00:41:35.990 --> 00:41:37.220
Eyeballs.

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:40.880
So what should I pay
attention to?

00:41:40.880 --> 00:41:41.990
Eyeballs.

00:41:41.990 --> 00:41:43.720
Here's how the eye works.

00:41:43.720 --> 00:41:47.080
It goes to a pattern that it
recognizes first in the area

00:41:47.080 --> 00:41:49.950
of light, then to dark.

00:41:49.950 --> 00:41:52.550
I want you to watch
a trend here.

00:41:52.550 --> 00:41:56.040
It then goes from high contrast
to low contrast.

00:41:56.040 --> 00:41:58.830
What is contrast?

00:41:58.830 --> 00:42:01.370
Bueller?

00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:04.540
The ratio between
light and dark.

00:42:04.540 --> 00:42:08.470
It goes from high sharpness
to low sharpness.

00:42:08.470 --> 00:42:10.700
What is sharpness, or
specifically, unsharpness?

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:13.430
And if we want to get really
technical, the

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:16.850
Craik-O'Brien-Cornsweet
edge illusion.

00:42:16.850 --> 00:42:17.960
What is that?

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:20.230
What is unsharpness
in a computer?

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:25.270
The introduction of contrast
to the edges of things.

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:27.150
The human eye is a
contrast beast.

00:42:27.150 --> 00:42:29.650
It works on varying degrees
of contrast.

00:42:29.650 --> 00:42:32.300
It then goes from in focus to
blur, which is different than

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:34.180
high to low sharpness.

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:37.260
High saturation of color to low
saturation of color, which

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:39.590
is another form of contrast.

00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:41.830
Warm colors move forward
in the picture.

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:44.210
Cool colors recede
in a picture.

00:42:44.210 --> 00:42:47.950
So my job is to control your eye
and where it goes, because

00:42:47.950 --> 00:42:50.950
the most important thing to keep
in mind is that the human

00:42:50.950 --> 00:42:52.360
eye doesn't want to
look at anything.

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:54.210
It's always in a seek mode.

00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:57.100
Women understand this concept
better than men.

00:42:57.100 --> 00:42:59.350
You're out on a date, a pretty
woman walks in, what

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:02.460
does the guy do?

00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:03.870
Always in the seek mode.

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:08.690
So my job is to create a
situation where you can't stop

00:43:08.690 --> 00:43:11.040
looking at the photograph.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:12.930
It's my picture, right?

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:17.470
I decide where the viewers eye
goes based on being true to

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:20.300
the emotional moment
that took me.

00:43:20.300 --> 00:43:22.480
So how do I do that?

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:29.330
Well, I use the middle part,
software, to control how

00:43:29.330 --> 00:43:30.540
things go about.

00:43:30.540 --> 00:43:34.010
Contrast, sharpness, light,
dark, detail enhancement,

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:37.050
detail degradation, blur.

00:43:37.050 --> 00:43:39.690
All of these things are things
that I try to do.

00:43:39.690 --> 00:43:44.050
Now, what I have found is
in-camera blur is better than

00:43:44.050 --> 00:43:47.380
digital blur, so what I try to
do is create images that will

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:50.520
give me the varying levels of
blur that I want and the

00:43:50.520 --> 00:43:54.040
varying levels of sharpness that
I want, that there's a

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:55.740
point where I start
looking at the

00:43:55.740 --> 00:43:57.100
picture as image structure.

00:43:57.100 --> 00:44:00.140
Now, there are two schools
of thought.

00:44:00.140 --> 00:44:03.250
There's a school of thought,
Ansel Adams school of thought,

00:44:03.250 --> 00:44:06.380
which says that without
previsualization, the zone

00:44:06.380 --> 00:44:09.060
system is just a five finger
exercise, so you need to

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:11.000
previsualize the photograph.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.440
And then there is Paul
Caponigro's school of thought,

00:44:13.440 --> 00:44:16.320
which is if you believe in
previsualization, you deserve

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:18.760
what you get.

00:44:18.760 --> 00:44:21.310
Both are correct.

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:25.250
You don't want to walk into a
situation previsualizing what

00:44:25.250 --> 00:44:27.980
picture you're going to take,
because all you're ever going

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:29.460
to do is be disappointed.

00:44:29.460 --> 00:44:32.030
Because the picture that you're
dreaming to see will

00:44:32.030 --> 00:44:33.900
never occur.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:36.470
What I previsualize when
I walk in to shoot, I

00:44:36.470 --> 00:44:39.490
previsualize being amazed.

00:44:39.490 --> 00:44:44.730
The moment I fire the shutter,
at that moment, I start

00:44:44.730 --> 00:44:48.110
previsualizing the
finished picture.

00:44:48.110 --> 00:44:52.320
When I was a kid growing up--
see, I turned that, right?

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:56.500
There was a poster that my
father had of a "Saturday

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:58.910
Evening Post" cover called
"The Connoisseur." It's a

00:44:58.910 --> 00:45:01.290
picture of a Jackson Pollock
scribble, and there's this guy

00:45:01.290 --> 00:45:04.900
standing like this, holding
a bowler hat and a pair of

00:45:04.900 --> 00:45:08.790
gloves, looking at this Jackson
Pollack scribble.

00:45:08.790 --> 00:45:12.080
Every time I take a picture, the
ones that really grab me,

00:45:12.080 --> 00:45:17.420
in that moment in my head, I put
the picture in that frame

00:45:17.420 --> 00:45:19.440
with that guy looking at it.

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:22.360
And so when I'm working on the
image in post-processing

00:45:22.360 --> 00:45:26.050
software, for me what it is is
removing everything that is

00:45:26.050 --> 00:45:28.930
not that picture, what

00:45:28.930 --> 00:45:30.830
Michelangelo said about sculpting.

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:33.830
He viewed the rock as a living
stone, and he removed

00:45:33.830 --> 00:45:36.540
everything that was not the
sculpture, and he freed the

00:45:36.540 --> 00:45:39.130
sculpture from the rock.

00:45:39.130 --> 00:45:42.570
The file is the living file,
and what I do is I free my

00:45:42.570 --> 00:45:46.060
vision of the image
from that file.

00:45:46.060 --> 00:45:48.650
And the thing you have to keep
in mind when you're working on

00:45:48.650 --> 00:45:56.820
an image is that magenta, kind
of puke yellow, low contrast

00:45:56.820 --> 00:45:59.320
file you're looking at that's
a raw file, that's the

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:01.870
cleanest the data
will ever be.

00:46:01.870 --> 00:46:05.630
Everything that you do to that
file from that moment forward,

00:46:05.630 --> 00:46:08.200
you're clipping data, and the
minute you clip data, you

00:46:08.200 --> 00:46:09.390
introduce artifact.

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:11.010
Correct?

00:46:11.010 --> 00:46:12.220
We all know that.

00:46:12.220 --> 00:46:15.310
Now, artifacting is both
cumulative and may be

00:46:15.310 --> 00:46:16.510
multiplicative.

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:18.120
And the goal is to--

00:46:18.120 --> 00:46:20.750
and this always sounds like
a Disney song to me--

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:26.170
minimize the cumulative and
negate the multiplicative.

00:46:26.170 --> 00:46:27.920
Can you see that being
a Disney song?

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:32.970
So the trick is in how you
post-process the image so that

00:46:32.970 --> 00:46:37.660
you negate the multiplication
aspects of artifacting, and

00:46:37.660 --> 00:46:42.396
you just deal with cumulative,
and you work at minimizing it.

00:46:42.396 --> 00:46:45.580
Which is why I use the tools I
use, and which is why I build

00:46:45.580 --> 00:46:46.370
things in layers.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:48.950
Instead of putting it all on one
layer, I have many layers.

00:46:48.950 --> 00:46:51.290
It's not because I like to
give myself busywork.

00:46:51.290 --> 00:46:53.670
It's because I like to make it
so that I can blow the picture

00:46:53.670 --> 00:46:56.790
up 16 feet if I want
to, because I

00:46:56.790 --> 00:46:59.260
minimize the artifact.

00:46:59.260 --> 00:47:01.590
The key elements of
a photograph--

00:47:01.590 --> 00:47:04.100
light, gesture, color.

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:05.820
That's Maisel.

00:47:05.820 --> 00:47:07.790
And if you're not familiar with
Jay Maisel, you should

00:47:07.790 --> 00:47:08.500
look him up.

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:10.180
I think he's probably the
greatest breathing

00:47:10.180 --> 00:47:12.520
photographer we have.

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:14.890
Mine, because I can't leave
well enough alone--

00:47:14.890 --> 00:47:18.510
light, gesture, color,
and time.

00:47:18.510 --> 00:47:20.030
Specifically, timeless.

00:47:20.030 --> 00:47:24.290
If you can create a photograph
where you have no idea when it

00:47:24.290 --> 00:47:30.420
was shot, those are truly the
most successful photographs.

00:47:30.420 --> 00:47:32.280
Here's a couple of things
that I've learned.

00:47:32.280 --> 00:47:36.110
Timeless in a city happens
four stories and above.

00:47:36.110 --> 00:47:36.785
Go to San Francisco.

00:47:36.785 --> 00:47:39.200
Next time you're in San
Francisco, look at where the

00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:44.210
banners end for the Giants
or the next exhibition at

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:45.665
whatever gallery.

00:47:45.665 --> 00:47:48.290
Look at where all
the neon ends.

00:47:48.290 --> 00:47:52.530
It ends at the bottom of the
third floor, at the beginning

00:47:52.530 --> 00:47:53.710
of the fourth floor.

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:57.300
If you shoot from the fourth
floor up, what you see is the

00:47:57.300 --> 00:48:02.715
age of the city when those
buildings were shot.

00:48:06.240 --> 00:48:06.880
There's another thing.

00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:09.480
There's a photographer
named [? Duino ?].

00:48:09.480 --> 00:48:11.540
I used to look at his work,
and he was one of those

00:48:11.540 --> 00:48:13.830
photographers for me which
whenever I looked at his

00:48:13.830 --> 00:48:16.190
pictures, it was,
I'm not worthy.

00:48:16.190 --> 00:48:18.550
I should go find a job where I
say "would you like fries with

00:48:18.550 --> 00:48:22.830
that?" I mean, just not worthy
to take a picture.

00:48:22.830 --> 00:48:24.070
His work was so amazing.

00:48:24.070 --> 00:48:26.930
His backgrounds were
so incredible.

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:30.790
So I did something that guys
don't normally do.

00:48:30.790 --> 00:48:32.850
Basically, I read the book.

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:36.050
Instead of looked at the book,
I read the instructions.

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:39.500
And he had one quote that just
stuck with me. "I find the

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:40.680
stage, and the

00:48:40.680 --> 00:48:44.270
players come." Brilliant!

00:48:44.270 --> 00:48:47.260
What the man would do is he
would go find the background,

00:48:47.260 --> 00:48:51.300
set the camera up, get it all
set, sit down, have a cup of

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:55.142
coffee, and wait for stuff
to walk into his picture.

00:48:55.142 --> 00:48:56.942
That's brilliant!

00:48:56.942 --> 00:49:01.390
That's absolutely the best
way to shoot, because the

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:04.160
background is as important
as the foreground.

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:07.130
And if your background is
interesting, and then you have

00:49:07.130 --> 00:49:10.130
an in-focus subject, the
picture's even more compelling

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:11.020
and interesting.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:14.240
So I would invite you to
consider, in your quest for

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:16.830
how do you make them better,
find the stage, and the

00:49:16.830 --> 00:49:18.960
players will come.

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:20.770
Pay attention to the background
as much as you pay

00:49:20.770 --> 00:49:23.550
attention to the foreground.

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:26.200
What's more important
in a photograph, the

00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:27.450
light or the subject?

00:49:29.755 --> 00:49:32.640
What do you think?

00:49:32.640 --> 00:49:33.870
Subject?

00:49:33.870 --> 00:49:34.350
OK.

00:49:34.350 --> 00:49:37.720
Do you know what the word
"photography" means?

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:40.760
Photo-graphy, "to write with
light." what would you rather

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:47.290
look at, the Taj Mahal poorly
lit or a line of clothing

00:49:47.290 --> 00:49:50.590
beautifully lit?

00:49:50.590 --> 00:49:57.330
Treat light as if it
was a solid object.

00:49:57.330 --> 00:50:00.270
It's as important to the
photograph, if not more

00:50:00.270 --> 00:50:02.880
important to the photograph,
sometimes

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:04.970
than the subject itself.

00:50:04.970 --> 00:50:07.650
If the light is beautiful,
all sorts of

00:50:07.650 --> 00:50:09.460
wonderful things happen.

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:10.850
Now, here's one for you.

00:50:10.850 --> 00:50:12.580
What's the fastest thing
in the universe?

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:21.230
Unless you're a Trekkie, then
it's tachyons, right?

00:50:24.283 --> 00:50:28.200
Doesn't it amaze you that dark
always seems to be there

00:50:28.200 --> 00:50:30.260
before light?

00:50:30.260 --> 00:50:32.620
Doesn't that trip you out?

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:35.060
Now, yes, light is the fastest
thing that we know of in the

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:38.140
universe, but dark in a
photograph is as important to

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:39.800
the photograph as light.

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:41.760
And the way in which
I remember that--

00:50:41.760 --> 00:50:44.150
Terry Pratchett came up
with that quote--

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:47.120
is that dark is always
there before it.

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:50.800
I need to have dark in my
photograph to have drama, to

00:50:50.800 --> 00:50:53.810
have contrast, to control the
ideas of the picture.

00:50:53.810 --> 00:50:56.170
I need to have in-focus,
I need to have blur.

00:50:56.170 --> 00:50:57.970
These are the elements
that I work with.

00:50:57.970 --> 00:51:02.390
That's why these lenses
are my brushes.

00:51:02.390 --> 00:51:07.250
These cameras, because of the
different resolutions, become

00:51:07.250 --> 00:51:11.490
my canvas that I paint on,
because I pick the camera that

00:51:11.490 --> 00:51:15.030
I'm going to use based on what
is the needs of what it is

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:17.020
that I'm going to do.

