Please?

01:05:06.880 --> 01:05:10.660
But yes, for you, the answer
is I picked that dissolve

01:05:10.660 --> 01:05:14.100
because it's the simplest, and
everything moves because it

01:05:14.100 --> 01:05:16.370
all tells a story.

01:05:16.370 --> 01:05:19.590
Where the first slide show was
set up, how it went from San

01:05:19.590 --> 01:05:24.150
Francisco to New York to Paris,
and then that last shot

01:05:24.150 --> 01:05:27.760
leads into the flowers that lead
into the portrait, which

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:30.400
is the landscapes
as portraits.

01:05:30.400 --> 01:05:33.570
So I'm trying to reinforce
the idea.

01:05:33.570 --> 01:05:35.160
Everything matters.

01:05:35.160 --> 01:05:38.650
Everything dovetails into
everything else.

01:05:38.650 --> 01:05:41.500
The answer to the question
is always, yes.

01:05:41.500 --> 01:05:44.230
If you say to yourself,
do you think the

01:05:44.230 --> 01:05:45.310
order my pictures matter?

01:05:45.310 --> 01:05:46.890
What's the answer?

01:05:46.890 --> 01:05:48.090
Yes.

01:05:48.090 --> 01:05:49.990
Should I shoot two more shots?

01:05:49.990 --> 01:05:50.270
Yes.

01:05:50.270 --> 01:05:52.190
Do you think-- yes.

01:05:52.190 --> 01:05:53.440
Uh-- yes.

01:05:55.660 --> 01:06:01.150
I had a very wise teacher
named Viola Spolin.

01:06:01.150 --> 01:06:01.710
She teaches improv.

01:06:01.710 --> 01:06:03.770
She created improv
as we know it.

01:06:03.770 --> 01:06:04.850
It's called Spolin technique.

01:06:04.850 --> 01:06:06.380
A very wise woman.

01:06:06.380 --> 01:06:10.560
Said at the point at which you
say it doesn't matter is the

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:14.560
point at which you say your
career or your character

01:06:14.560 --> 01:06:16.090
doesn't matter.

01:06:16.090 --> 01:06:17.030
Everything matters.

01:06:17.030 --> 01:06:22.130
You just don't know what
significance is until the

01:06:22.130 --> 01:06:25.260
large, operatic lady sings.

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:27.850
So I apply that to this.

01:06:27.850 --> 01:06:30.120
At the point at which you say
it doesn't matter in your

01:06:30.120 --> 01:06:31.490
image is the point at
which you say your

01:06:31.490 --> 01:06:32.710
image doesn't matter.

01:06:32.710 --> 01:06:33.680
Everything matters.

01:06:33.680 --> 01:06:36.070
You just don't know what's
significant until you make the

01:06:36.070 --> 01:06:38.380
less pixel sing.

01:06:38.380 --> 01:06:41.270
So the job is to consider
everything.

01:06:41.270 --> 01:06:44.360
Some things are more important
than others, but consider

01:06:44.360 --> 01:06:46.140
everything.

01:06:46.140 --> 01:06:49.750
Which leads to I used to
have hair down to here.

01:06:49.750 --> 01:06:53.720
Now I have no hair, because
I'm worrying about every

01:06:53.720 --> 01:06:54.350
little thing.

01:06:54.350 --> 01:06:58.070
So that when I put the
photograph up, what is not

01:06:58.070 --> 01:07:02.000
there is any reason to take
you out of the experience,

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:05.280
that the landscaping of the
photograph matters.

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:07.580
Now, I'm going to show
you something, why

01:07:07.580 --> 01:07:10.900
infrared is way cool.

01:07:10.900 --> 01:07:14.270
This is a picture
of a young girl.

01:07:14.270 --> 01:07:18.450
Now, this is shot infrared, and
all three of the pictures

01:07:18.450 --> 01:07:21.150
that I'm going to show you
were shot with the same

01:07:21.150 --> 01:07:24.320
camera, one modified for
infrared, one not modified for

01:07:24.320 --> 01:07:26.360
infrared, using the same lens.

01:07:26.360 --> 01:07:27.600
And the shot was done this.

01:07:27.600 --> 01:07:31.386
Click, click click.

01:07:31.386 --> 01:07:32.810
See this?

01:07:32.810 --> 01:07:34.060
Pretty, right?

01:07:37.710 --> 01:07:38.960
Pretty, right?

01:07:42.140 --> 01:07:43.080
Exactly.

01:07:43.080 --> 01:07:45.810
Not that it's not pretty, but
there's a profound difference

01:07:45.810 --> 01:07:49.280
between this and this.

01:07:49.280 --> 01:07:52.252
What do you think that is?

01:07:52.252 --> 01:07:52.700
Eyes.

01:07:52.700 --> 01:07:54.580
What else?

01:07:54.580 --> 01:07:57.160
It's the glow.

01:07:57.160 --> 01:08:01.430
What you're looking at is near
visible spectrum light, light

01:08:01.430 --> 01:08:05.470
you can't see but you can feel
and you're aware of.

01:08:05.470 --> 01:08:07.890
I can't explain this, and
forgive me if I sound like an

01:08:07.890 --> 01:08:11.360
airy, fairy artist because,
well, I'm about to become an

01:08:11.360 --> 01:08:13.720
airy fairy artist.

01:08:13.720 --> 01:08:15.980
It's as if there's another
universe I'm photographing

01:08:15.980 --> 01:08:19.100
that I can't see, that when I
photograph it feels like I'm

01:08:19.100 --> 01:08:22.660
looking at something that
happened 100 years ago.

01:08:22.660 --> 01:08:24.060
It's the wildest thing.

01:08:24.060 --> 01:08:26.840
It's why I fell in love
with infrared.

01:08:26.840 --> 01:08:30.760
You're photographing near
visible spectrum, and you're

01:08:30.760 --> 01:08:34.130
photographing some small
degree of heat.

01:08:34.130 --> 01:08:35.950
But to truly photograph
infrared, you need to cool

01:08:35.950 --> 01:08:37.300
down the sensor.

01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:41.080
But that's what causes the glow,
I think, is the heat

01:08:41.080 --> 01:08:42.490
aspect of the light.

01:08:42.490 --> 01:08:45.350
That's just me guessing, so
I'm not basing that on

01:08:45.350 --> 01:08:48.149
anything other than having shot
it for eight years and

01:08:48.149 --> 01:08:49.770
looking at it.

